# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fermentation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:fermentation/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:fermentation/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] Reduction of CO2 to acetic acid via the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway requires an electron source (e.g., H2, CO, formate, etc.).
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] When acetogens are grown autotrophically, they synthesize acetic acid only through the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway; but when they are grown heterotrophically, they can produce additional acetic acid by oxidation of the carbon source (carbohydrates, organic acids, or alcohols).
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] Once produced, acetyl-CoA can be incorporated into biomass or converted to acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] In 1932, organisms were discovered that could convert hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide into acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] The first acetogenic bacterium species, *Clostridium aceticum*, was discovered in 1936 by Klaas Tammo Wieringa.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] A second species, *Moorella thermoacetica*, attracted wide interest because of its ability, reported in 1942, to convert glucose into three moles of acetic acid, a process called homoacetate fermentation.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] The precursor to acetic acid is the thioester acetyl CoA.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] The key aspects of the acetogenic pathway are several reactions that include the reduction of carbon dioxide (CO2) to carbon monoxide (CO) and the attachment of CO to a methyl group (–CH3) and coenzyme A.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] The first process is catalyzed by enzymes called carbon monoxide dehydrogenase.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] The coupling of the methyl group (provided by methylcobalamin), the CO, and the coenzyme A is catalyzed by acetyl-CoA synthase.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] However, what matters for the cell is how much ATP is generated.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] The unique metabolism of acetogens has significance in biotechnological uses.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] In carbohydrate fermentations, the decarboxylation reactions end in the conversion of organic carbon into carbon dioxide.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] In the production of biofuels, the need to reduce CO2 emissions, as well as the need to be competitive, means that this inefficiency should perhaps be eliminated by using acetogens.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] Acetogenesis does not replace glycolysis with a different pathway but rather captures the CO2 from glycolysis and uses it to produce acetic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetogenesis] Although three molecules of acetic acid can be produced in this way, production of three molecules of ethanol would require an additional reducing agent such as hydrogen gas.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The process may be likened to how yeast ferments sugars to produce ethanol for wine, beer, or fuel, but the organisms that carry out the ABE fermentation are strictly anaerobic (obligate anaerobes).
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation produces solvents in a ratio of 3 parts acetone, 6 parts butanol to 1 part ethanol.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It usually uses a strain of bacteria from class Clostridia (family Clostridiaceae).
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] *Clostridium acetobutylicum* is the most well-studied and widely used.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although less effective, *Clostridium beijerinckii* and *Clostridium saccharobutylicum* bacterial strains have shown good results as well.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation pathway generally proceeds in two phases.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the initial acidogenesis phase, the cells grow exponentially and accumulate acetate and butyrate.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The low pH along with other factors then trigger a metabolic shift to the solventogenesis phase, in which acetate and butyrate are used to produce the solvents.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For gas stripping, the most common gases used are the off-gases from the fermentation itself, a mixture of carbon dioxide and hydrogen gas.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The production of butanol by biological means was first performed by Louis Pasteur in 1861.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1905, Austrian biochemist Franz Schardinger found that acetone could similarly be produced.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1910 Auguste Fernbach (1860–1939) developed a bacterial fermentation process using potato starch as a feedstock in the production of butanol.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Industrial exploitation of ABE fermentation started in 1916, during World War I, with Chaim Weizmann's isolation of Clostridium acetobutylicum, as described in U.S. patent 1315585.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Weizmann process was operated by Commercial Solvents Corporation from about 1920 to 1964 with plants in the US (Terre Haute, IN, and Peoria, IL), and Liverpool, England.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Peoria plant was the largest of the three.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It used molasses as feedstock and had 96 fermenters with a volume of 96,000 gallons each.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] After World War II, ABE fermentation became generally non-profitable, compared to the production of the same three solvents (acetone, butanol, ethanol) from petroleum.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] During the 1950s and 1960s, ABE fermentation was replaced by petroleum chemical plants.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Due to different raw material costs, ABE fermentation was viable in South Africa until the early 1980s, with the last plant closing in 1983.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd operated the last attempt to resurrect the process at scale but the plant closed in Minnesota in June 2019.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] A new ABE biorefinery has been developed in Scotland by Celtic Renewables Ltd and began production in 2023.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The key difference in the process is the use of low value spent materials or residues from other processes removing the variable costs of raw feedstock crops and materials.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The most critical aspect in biomass fermentation processes is related to its productivity.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation via *Clostridium beijerinckii* or *Clostridium acetobutylicum* for instance is characterized by product inhibition.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This means that there is a product concentration threshold that cannot be overcome, resulting in a product stream highly diluted in water.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, in order to have a comparable productivity and profitability with respect to the petrochemical processes, cost and energy effective solutions for the product purification sections are required to provide a significant product recovery at the desired purity.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the second half of the 20th century, these technologies allowed an increase in the final product concentration in the broth from 15 to 30 g/L, an increase in the final productivity from 0.46 to 4.6 g/(L*h) and an increase in the yield from 15 to 42%.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] From a compound purification perspective, the main criticalities in the ABE/W product recovery are due to the water–alcohol mixture's non-ideal interactions leading to homogeneous and heterogeneous azeotropic species, as shown by the ternary equilibrium diagram.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This causes the separation by standard distillation to be particularly impractical but, on the other hand, allows the exploitation of the liquid–liquid demixing region both for analogous and alternative separation processes.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Therefore, in order to enhance the ABE fermentation yield, mainly in situ product recovery systems have been developed.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] These include gas stripping, pervaporation, liquid–liquid extraction, distillation via Dividing Wall Column, membrane distillation, membrane separation, adsorption, and reverse osmosis.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd. implemented many of these technologies at an industrial scale.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, differently from crude oil feedstocks, biomasses nature fluctuates over the year's seasons and according to the geographical location.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] ABE fermentation is attracting renewed interest with a focus on butanol as a renewable biofuel.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Sustainability is by far the topic of major concern over the last years.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The energy challenge is the key point of the environmental friendly policies adopted by all the most developed and industrialized countries worldwide.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this purpose Horizon 2020, the biggest EU Research and Innovation programme, was funded by the European Union over the 2014–2020 period.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The International Energy Agency defines renewables as the centre of the transition to a less carbon-intensive and more sustainable energy system.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biofuels are believed to represent around 30% of energy consumption in transport by 2060.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Their role is particularly important in sectors which are difficult to decarbonise, such as aviation, shipping and other long-haul transport.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] That is why several bioprocesses have seen a renewed interest in recent years, both from a research and an industrial perspective.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, the ABE fermentation process has been reconsidered from a different perspective.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although it was originally conceived to produce acetone, it is considered as a suitable production pathway for biobutanol that has become the product of major interest.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biogenic butanol is a possible substitute of bioethanol or even better and it is already employed both as fuel additive and as pure fuel instead of standard gasoline because, differently from ethanol, it can be directly and efficiently used in gasoline engines.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, it has the advantage that it can be shipped and distributed through existing pipelines and filling stations.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Finally biobutanol is widely used as a direct solvent for paints, coatings, varnishes, resins, dyes, camphor, vegetable oils, fats, waxes, shellac, rubbers and alkaloids due to its higher energy density, lower volatility, and lower hygroscopicity.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It can be produced from different kinds of cellulosic biomass and can be used for further processing of advanced biofuels such as butyl levulinate as well.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The application of n-butanol in the production of butyl acrylate has a wide scope for its expansion, which in turn would help in increasing the consumption of n-butanol globally.
[src:fermentation/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Butyl acrylate was the biggest n-butanol application in 2014 and is projected to be worth US$3.9 billion by 2020.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Coenzyme A (CoASH or CoA) consists of a β-mercaptoethylamine group linked to pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) through an amide linkage and 3'-phosphorylated ADP.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] The acetyl group (indicated in blue in the structural diagram on the right) of acetyl-CoA is linked to the sulfhydryl substituent of the β-mercaptoethylamine group.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] This thioester linkage is a "high energy" bond, which is particularly reactive.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Hydrolysis of the thioester bond is exergonic (−31.5 kJ/mol).
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] CoA is acetylated to acetyl-CoA by the breakdown of carbohydrates through glycolysis and by the breakdown of fatty acids through β-oxidation.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA then enters the citric acid cycle, where the acetyl group is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, and the energy released is captured in the form of 11 ATP and one GTP per acetyl group.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Konrad Bloch and Feodor Lynen were awarded the 1964 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries linking acetyl-CoA and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Fritz Lipmann won the Nobel Prize in 1953 for his discovery of the cofactor coenzyme A.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is a metabolic intermediate that is involved in many metabolic pathways in an organism.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] It is produced during the breakdown of glucose, fatty acids, and amino acids, and is used in the synthesis of many other biomolecules, including cholesterol, fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also a key molecule in the citric acid cycle, which is a series of chemical reactions that occur in the mitochondria of cells and is responsible for generating energy in the form of ATP.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] In addition, acetyl-CoA is a precursor for the biosynthesis of various acetyl-chemicals, acting as an intermediate to transfer an acetyl group during the biosynthesis of those acetyl-chemicals.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also involved in the regulation of various cellular mechanisms by providing acetyl groups to target amino acid residues for post-translational acetylation reactions of proteins.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] The acetylation of CoA is determined by the carbon sources.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, glycolysis takes place rapidly, thus increasing the amount of citrate produced from the citric acid cycle.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] This citrate is then exported to other organelles outside the mitochondria to be broken into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate by the enzyme ATP citrate lyase (ACL).
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] This principal reaction is coupled with the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels CoA is acetylated using acetate by acetyl-CoA synthetase (ACS), also coupled with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Ethanol also serves as a carbon source for acetylation of CoA utilizing the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Degradation of branched-chain ketogenic amino acids such as valine, leucine, and isoleucine occurs.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] These amino acids are converted to α-ketoacids by transamination and eventually to isovaleryl-CoA through oxidative decarboxylation by an α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Isovaleryl-CoA undergoes dehydrogenation, carboxylation and hydration to form another CoA-derivative intermediate before it is cleaved into acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Additionally, malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), present in the cytosol, contributes to the extramitochondrial acetyl-CoA pool by converting malonyl-CoA into acetyl-CoA.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, acetyl-CoA is produced through glycolysis.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Pyruvate undergoes oxidative decarboxylation in which it loses its carboxyl group (as carbon dioxide) to form acetyl-CoA, giving off 33.5 kJ/mol of energy.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] The oxidative conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA is referred to as the **pyruvate dehydrogenase reaction**.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] It is catalyzed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Other conversions between pyruvate and acetyl-CoA are possible.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] For example, pyruvate formate lyase disproportionates pyruvate into acetyl-CoA and formic acid.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels, the production of acetyl-CoA is linked to β-oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Fatty acids are first converted to acyl-CoA.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is then degraded in a four-step cycle of oxidation, hydration, oxidation and thiolysis catalyzed by four respective enzymes, namely acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, enoyl-CoA hydratase, 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase, and thiolase.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] The cycle produces a new fatty acid chain with two fewer carbons and acetyl-CoA as a byproduct.
[src:fermentation/acetyl-coa] Within mitochondria, MCD similarly facilitates acetyl-CoA production by decarboxylating malonyl-CoA, thereby supporting metabolic flexibility during low-glucose states.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:fermentation/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:fermentation/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermentation is important in several areas of human society.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Humans have used fermentation in the production and preservation of food for 13,000 years.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It has been associated with health benefits, unique flavor profiles, and making products have better texture.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Humans and their livestock also benefit from fermentation from the microbes in the gut that release end products that are subsequently used by the host for energy.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Perhaps the most commonly known use for fermentation is at an industrial level to produce commodity chemicals, such as ethanol and lactate.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Ethanol is used in a variety of alcoholic beverages (beers, wine, and spirits) while lactate can be neutralized to lactic acid and be used for food preservation, as a curing agent, or as a flavoring agent.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This complex metabolism utilizes a wide variety of substrates and can form nearly 300 different combinations of end products.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermentation occurs in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The discovery of new end products and new fermentative organisms suggests that fermentation is more diverse than what has been studied.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] However, this definition does not encompass all forms of fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] For example, propionate fermentation which uses H2 as an electron donor, or the second step of butyrate fermentation where CO2 can act as an electron acceptor.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Thus, it is simplest to use this definition while acknowledging that protons can also be used as electron donors and CO2 as acceptors.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In 1876, before the discovery of anaerobic respiration, Louis Pasteur described it as "la vie sans air" (life without air).
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It was also common for fermentation to be defined based on how fermentation forms ATP which was catabolism that forms ATP through only substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Industrial fermentation is another type of fermentation that is defined loosely as a large-scale biological manufacturing process; however, this definition focuses on the process of manufacturing rather than metabolic details.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermentation can be used by organisms to generate a net gain of ATP from exogenous sources of organic molecules, such as glucose.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It was not a net source of energy in the earliest forms of life because they were mostly single cell organisms living in the ocean and the ocean does not contain significant concentrations of complex organic molecules.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Because fermentation does not need an exogenous electron acceptor, it is able to occur regardless of the environmental conditions.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] However, the primary disadvantage of fermentation is that fermentation is relatively inefficient and produces between 2 and 5 ATP molecules per glucose versus 32 ATP molecules during aerobic respiration.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Over 25% of bacteria and archaea carry out fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermentation is especially prevalent in prokaryotes of the phylum Bacillota, but is most rare in Actinomycetota, according to phylogenetic analysis.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The fermenting microbes are most frequently found in host-associated habitats such as the gastrointestinal tract, but also sediments, food, and other habitats.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Both bacteria and archaea share the capacity for fermentation, leading to a wide variety of organic end products.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The most common fermentation products include lactate, acetate, ethanol, carbon dioxide (CO2), succinate, hydrogen (H2), propionate, and butyrate.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In humans, fermentation pathways occur in health, as in exercising, and in disease, as in sepsis and hemorrhagic shock, providing energy for a period ranging from 10 seconds to 2 minutes.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] During this time, it can augment the energy produced by aerobic metabolism, but is limited by the buildup of lactate.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Like many biochemical reactions, fermentation is an enzyme catalyzed reaction with the goal of either changing the initial substrate or forming a useful byproduct.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] When naturally occurring fermentation is carried out by microbes, the goal is usually to obtain useful metabolic products such as ATP, pyruvate, or lactic acid.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The substrates used in this type of fermentation are often simple sugars (carbohydrates) that serve as a carbon source and this type of fermentation can be carried out by microbes and humans.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Food as a substrate for fermentation is the most common and oldest anthropogenic use of fermentation as it was a method to preserve food.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This includes cereal, dairy products, rice, honey, bread, and beers.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This type of naturally occurring fermentation continues to be harnessed by humans for preservative effects, flavor profiles, and texture profiles.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Advances in fermentation has led to the engineering and industrialization of specific microbes and substrates in order to obtain certain flavor and texture profiles – this is most obvious when observing beer fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] When an organic compound is fermented, it is broken down to a simpler molecule and releases electrons.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The electrons are transferred to a redox cofactor, which, in turn, transfers them to an organic compound.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] ATP is generated in the process, and it can be formed via substrate-level phosphorylation or by ATP synthase.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] When glucose is fermented, it enters glycolysis or the pentose phosphate pathway and is converted to pyruvate.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] From pyruvate, pathways branch out to form a number of end products (e.g. lactate).
[src:fermentation/fermentation] At several points, electrons are released and accepted by redox cofactors (NAD and ferredoxin).
[src:fermentation/fermentation] At later points, these cofactors donate electrons to their final acceptor and become oxidized.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] ATP is also formed at several points in the pathway.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Yeast and other anaerobic microorganisms can convert the pyruvate produced from the oxidation of glucose by a glycolysis pathway to ethanol and CO2.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In ethanol fermentation, one glucose molecule is converted into two ethanol molecules and two carbon dioxide (CO2) molecules.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It is used to make bread dough rise: the carbon dioxide forms bubbles, expanding the dough into a foam.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The ethanol is the intoxicating agent in alcoholic beverages such as wine, beer and liquor.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermentation of feedstocks, including sugarcane, maize, and sugar beets, produces ethanol that is added to gasoline.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In some species of fish, such as carp, it provides energy when oxygen is scarce (along with lactic acid fermentation).
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Before fermentation, a glucose molecule breaks down into two pyruvate molecules (glycolysis).
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The energy from this exothermic reaction is used to bind inorganic phosphates to ADP, which converts it to ATP, and convert NAD+ to NADH.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The pyruvates break down into two acetaldehyde molecules and give off two carbon dioxide molecules as waste products.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The acetaldehyde is reduced into ethanol using the energy and hydrogen from NADH, and the NADH is oxidized into NAD+ so that the cycle may repeat.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The reaction is catalyzed by the enzymes pyruvate decarboxylase and alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The history of ethanol as a fuel spans several centuries and is marked by a series of significant milestones.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Samuel Morey, an American inventor, was the first to produce ethanol by fermenting corn in 1826.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] However, it was not until the California Gold Rush in the 1850s that ethanol was first used as a fuel in the United States.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Rudolf Diesel demonstrated his engine, which could run on vegetable oils and ethanol, in 1895, but the widespread use of petroleum-based diesel engines made ethanol less popular as a fuel.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In the 1970s, the oil crisis reignited interest in ethanol, and Brazil became a leader in ethanol production and use.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The United States began producing ethanol on a large scale in the 1980s and 1990s as a fuel additive to gasoline, due to government regulations.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Today, ethanol continues to be explored as a sustainable and renewable fuel source, with researchers developing new technologies and biomass sources for its production.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Pyruvate is the terminal electron acceptor in lactic acid fermentation, and *homolactic fermentation* (producing only lactic acid) is the simplest type of fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Pyruvate from glycolysis undergoes a simple redox reaction, forming lactic acid.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It occurs in the muscles of animals when they need energy faster than the blood can supply oxygen.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] (In mammals, lactate can be transformed by the liver back into glucose using the Cori cycle.) It also occurs in some kinds of bacteria (such as lactobacilli) and some fungi.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It is the type of bacteria that convert lactose into lactic acid in yogurt, giving it its sour taste.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Heterolactic fermentation is in a sense intermediate between lactic acid fermentation and other types, e.g. alcoholic fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Hydrogen gas is produced in many types of fermentation as a way to regenerate NAD+ from NADH.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Electrons are transferred to ferredoxin, which in turn is oxidized by hydrogenase, producing H2.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Hydrogen gas is a substrate for methanogens and sulfate reducers, which keep the concentration of hydrogen low and favor the production of such an energy-rich compound, but hydrogen gas at a fairly high concentration can nevertheless be formed, as in flatus.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] For example, *Clostridium pasteurianum* ferments glucose to butyrate, acetate, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen gas.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Glyoxylate fermentation is a type of fermentation used by microbes that are able to utilize glyoxylate as a nitrogen source.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Other types of fermentation include mixed acid fermentation, butanediol fermentation, butyrate fermentation, caproate fermentation, and acetone–butanol–ethanol fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In food and industrial contexts, any chemical modification performed by a living being in a controlled container can be termed "fermentation".
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermentation can be used to make alternative protein sources.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It is commonly used to modify existing protein foods, including plant-based ones such as soy, into more flavorful forms such as tempeh and fermented tofu.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] More modern "fermentation" makes recombinant protein to help produce meat analogue, milk substitute, cheese analogues, and egg substitutes.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Heme proteins such as myoglobin and hemoglobin give meat its characteristic texture, flavor, color, and aroma.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The myoglobin and leghemoglobin ingredients can be used to replicate this property, despite them coming from a vat instead of meat.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Industrial fermentation can be used for enzyme production, where proteins with catalytic activity are produced and secreted by microorganisms.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The development of fermentation processes, microbial strain engineering and recombinant gene technologies has enabled the commercialization of a wide range of enzymes.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Enzymes are used in all kinds of industrial segments, such as food (lactose removal, cheese flavor), beverage (juice treatment), baking (bread softness, dough conditioning), animal feed, detergents (protein, starch and lipid stain removal), textile, personal care and pulp and paper industries.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Most industrial fermentation uses batch or fed-batch procedures, although continuous fermentation can be more economical if various challenges, particularly the difficulty of maintaining sterility, can be met.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In a batch process, all the ingredients are combined and the reactions proceed without any further input.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Batch fermentation has been used for millennia to make bread and alcoholic beverages, and it is still a common method, especially when the process is not well understood.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] However, it can be expensive because the fermentor must be sterilized using high pressure steam between batches.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Strictly speaking, there is often addition of small quantities of chemicals to control the pH or suppress foaming.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Batch fermentation goes through a series of phases.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] There is a lag phase in which cells adjust to their environment; then a phase in which exponential growth occurs.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Once many of the nutrients have been consumed, the growth slows and becomes non-exponential, but production of *secondary metabolites* (including commercially important antibiotics and enzymes) accelerates.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This continues through a stationary phase after most of the nutrients have been consumed, and then the cells die.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fed-batch fermentation is a variation of batch fermentation where some of the ingredients are added during the fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This allows greater control over the stages of the process.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In particular, production of secondary metabolites can be increased by adding a limited quantity of nutrients during the non-exponential growth phase.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fed-batch operations are often sandwiched between batch operations.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The high cost of sterilizing the fermentor between batches can be avoided using various open fermentation approaches that are able to resist contamination.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] One is to use a naturally evolved mixed culture.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This is particularly favored in wastewater treatment, since mixed populations can adapt to a wide variety of wastes.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Thermophilic bacteria can produce lactic acid at temperatures of around 50 °Celsius, sufficient to discourage microbial contamination; and ethanol has been produced at a temperature of 70 °C.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This is just below its boiling point (78 °C), making it easy to extract.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Halophilic bacteria can produce bioplastics in hypersaline conditions.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Solid-state fermentation adds a small amount of water to a solid substrate; it is widely used in the food industry to produce flavors, enzymes and organic acids.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In continuous fermentation, substrates are added and final products removed continuously.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] There are three varieties: chemostats, which hold nutrient levels constant; turbidostats, which keep cell mass constant; and plug flow reactors in which the culture medium flows steadily through a tube while the cells are recycled from the outlet to the inlet.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] If the process works well, there is a steady flow of feed and effluent and the costs of repeatedly setting up a batch are avoided.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Also, it can prolong the exponential growth phase and avoid byproducts that inhibit the reactions by continuously removing them.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] However, it is difficult to maintain a steady state and avoid contamination, and the design tends to be complex.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Typically the fermentor must run for over 500 hours to be more economical than batch processors.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermented foods have a religious significance in Judaism and Christianity.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The Baltic god Rugutis was worshiped as the agent of fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The 'father of modern chemistry', Antoine Lavoisier, had viewed fermentation as a simple chemical reaction and rejected the notion that living organisms could be involved.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] By the 19th century, this was seen as vitalism, which was lampooned in an anonymous 1839 publication by Justus von Liebig and Friedrich Wöhler.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In 1837, Charles Cagniard de la Tour, Theodor Schwann and Friedrich Traugott Kützing independently published papers concluding, as a result of microscopic investigations, that yeast is a living organism that reproduces by budding.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Schwann boiled grape juice to kill the yeast and found that no fermentation would occur until new yeast was added.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The turning point came when Louis Pasteur (1822–1895), during the 1850s and 1860s, repeated Schwann's experiments and showed fermentation is initiated by living organisms in a series of investigations.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In 1857, Pasteur showed lactic acid fermentation is caused by living organisms.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In 1860, he demonstrated how bacteria cause souring in milk, a process formerly thought to be merely a chemical change.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] His work in identifying the role of microorganisms in food spoilage led to the process of pasteurization.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In 1877, working to improve the French brewing industry, Pasteur published his famous paper on fermentation, "*Etudes sur la Bière*", which was translated into English in 1879 as "Studies on fermentation".
[src:fermentation/fermentation] He defined fermentation (incorrectly) as "Life without air".
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Although showing fermentation resulted from the action of living microorganisms was a breakthrough, it did not explain the basic nature of fermentation; nor did it prove it is caused by microorganisms which appear to be always present.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Many scientists, including Pasteur, had unsuccessfully attempted to extract the fermentation enzyme from yeast.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Success came in 1897 when the German chemist Eduard Buechner ground up yeast, extracted a juice from them, then found to his amazement this "dead" liquid would ferment a sugar solution, forming carbon dioxide and alcohol much like living yeasts.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Buechner's results are considered to mark the birth of biochemistry.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The "unorganized ferments" behaved just like the organized ones.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] From that time on, the term enzyme came to be applied to all ferments.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] It was then understood fermentation is caused by enzymes produced by microorganisms.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In 1907, Buechner won the Nobel Prize in chemistry for his work.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Advances in microbiology and fermentation technology have continued steadily up until the present.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] For example, in the 1930s, it was discovered microorganisms could be mutated with physical and chemical treatments to be higher-yielding, faster-growing, tolerant of less oxygen, and able to use a more concentrated medium.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The field of fermentation has been critical to producing a wide range of consumer goods, from food and drink to industrial chemicals and pharmaceuticals.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Since its early beginnings in ancient civilizations, fermentation has continued to evolve and expand, with new techniques and technologies driving advances in product quality, yield, and efficiency.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In the 1970s and 1980s, fermentation became increasingly important in producing bulk chemicals like ethanol, lactic acid, and citric acid.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This led to developing new fermentation techniques and genetically engineered microorganisms to improve yields and reduce production costs.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In the 1990s and 2000s, there was a growing interest in fermentation to produce functional foods and nutraceuticals, which have potential health benefits beyond basic nutrition.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] This led to new fermentation processes, probiotics, and other functional ingredients.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Recent research has begun to investigate the relationship between fermentation and creating a circular economy in effort to address the current climate crisis and the increasing demands for resources as the population grows.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The production of fuels, materials, and other chemicals has led to a notable increase in greenhouse gasses and a subsequent increase in global temperatures.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The current, linear economy relies heavily on fossil fuels and nonrenewable energy to produce chemicals and materials.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] In a circular economy, the use of renewable resources would be employed to produce chemicals; moreover, this type of economy focuses on reusing end-of-life chemicals and materials.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Investigation into alternative biofuels and biomaterials has become increasingly popular with fermentation as a notable method.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The primary source of biomass for fermentation is using biomass feedstocks which contain a mix of carbohydrates, proteins, oils and fats, and lignin.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Carbohydrates such as sucrose and starch (sources include sugarcane, corn, and cassava) are the most commonly used substrate for fermentation; however, in the discussion of biofuels, there are concerns regarding land competition between food and fuel biomass.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Attention has been turned towards second-generation biomass feedstock such as silvergrass or wood chips.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Anerobic digestion is found in all facets of biomass fermentation to create biofuels, biobased materials, and biochemicals.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] One of the most popular and established anaerobic fermentation process is the transformation of organic waste into biogas.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Further research has explored the possibility and reusing residual solids left over from fermentative processes and converting them into "char-based materials".
[src:fermentation/fermentation] If successful, this would promote increased efficiency and a decreased environmental impact in the biomanufacturing industry.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Additionally, homogenous gas streams of CO2, and CH4, can be formed from anaerobic digestion by some bacteria, while other bacteria are able to fixate CO2 or CO and convert them into alcohols or fatty acids.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] One the most widely known biobased chemicals produced through fermentation, the process of fermenting sugars from plants into ethanol and CO2 uses *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Biobased ethanol is used as a popular renewable transportation fuel and also holds value in the chemical industry as the precursor for ethylene, which can be converted into polyethylene.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Commercial bioethanol production via fermentation is dominant in Brazil and the USA and employs sugarcane and starch from corn as feedstocks.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The process involves starch enzymatic hydrolysis to glucose, followed by fermentation and distillation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] There were around 200 ethanol plants operating in the U.S. as of 2021, with capacities of production varying from 6 kilotonnes to over one million tonnes annually.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Succinic acid is an important biobased chemical utilized for the production of biodegradable polymers including polybutylene succinate (PBS) and as feedstock to other biobased chemicals like 1,4-butanediol.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Succinic acid can be produced via the fermentation of sugar and carbon dioxide using native strains of bacteria; however, yields depend upon strain and conditions.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Neutral or acidic fermentations are feasible, with low-pH fermentations facilitated by acid-resistant yeast strains simplifying downstream recovery through avoiding neutralization and reacidification.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Throughout the 2010s, several companies ordered commercial-scale production facilities, e.g., BioAmber, Myriant, Reverdia, and Succinity, on different host organisms and feedstocks like corn syrup and sorghum starch.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] While having proven the technical feasibility of succinic acid large-scale biobased production, most of them failed to compete economically with petrochemical products on a commercial scale.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Several of the plants were spun off or shut down to new proprietors, demonstrating the financial challenges of scaling up bio-based platforms within current markets.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] However, these projects are evidence that under right market conditions, succinic acid biobased has promise for greater industrial use.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fermentation plays a significant role in producing precursor polymers to products and food additives such as amino acids, organic acids, triglycerides and fatty acids.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Amino acids are industrially produced through fermentation by microorganisms such as *Corynebacterium glutamicum* and *Escherichia coli*.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The global market application for amino acids is primarily food and feed additive.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] L-glutamic acid and L-lysine are the most commonly found amino acids in this market with L-glutamic acid being mainly used as a food flavoring in the form of monosodium glutamate (MSG) and L-lysine being mainly used as an animal feed supplement.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Other amino acids like L-threonine and L-phenylalanine are also produced on large scales for different applications.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Organic acids such as citric acid, lactic acid, and acetic acid are procured by microbial fermentation.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Citric acid finds widespread use in the food industry as a preservative and flavoring agent.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Lactic acid is used in food preservation and as a precursor for biodegradable plastics.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Acetic acid is used in food as vinegar and as a chemical reagent in industries.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] These organic acids are produced using microorganisms like *Aspergillus niger* and *Lactobacillus* species under controlled fermentation conditions.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Fatty acids and triglycerides are produced by fermentation on oleaginous microorganisms such as *Yarrowia lipolytica* and certain fungi.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] These microorganisms can accumulate lipids under specific culture conditions and therefore are suitable for industrial-scale production of lipids.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The fatty acids produced can be used in the manufacture of soaps, detergents, and as starting compounds for various chemicals.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] Triglycerides are energy storage compounds with applications in the food industry and biofuel sector.
[src:fermentation/fermentation] The fermentation processes involve the optimization of environmental conditions and nutrient composition for maximum lipid accumulation.
